1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:28,560
 Some have written and talked about the surprising phenomenon of LLMs sounding more human, but I think the deeper concern is actually that we start to sound more like them, and that we start to mirror the outputs of LLMs, and there's a lot of research suggesting that's already happening, and I think that's where we start, and again, we've got the anthropology, we've got the experience, the 2000 years of wisdom of the church, we have to start by identifying what are the problems and opportunities, and how do we apply specifically to those problems.

2
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:45,680
 Well, Dr. Aaron Dominguez,John_Brahier, it's fantastic to be with you guys today as the Builders AI conference is going on, so thank you for joining me in the Gregorian studio here.

3
00:00:45,680 --> 00:00:52,120
 Well, thank you, thank you for having us, I'm really excited to talk to you today, and really excited to be here, participating in this conference.

4
00:00:52,120 --> 00:00:58,720
 How is AI already transforming classrooms, research, and administration?

5
00:00:58,720 --> 00:01:14,360
 I'm kind of an early adopter kind of guy with my tech background, so I've been using all these tools for quite some time now, and it's made me way more efficient, which is, I think, the good aspects of these set of tools.

6
00:01:14,360 --> 00:01:28,680
 But no, it's here, it's here to stay, and at the conference last year, I was getting ready to launch a new bachelor's degree and master's degree in AI for our students from a Catholic perspective.

7
00:01:28,720 --> 00:01:32,800
 And incorporating our ethics and the magisterium of the church.

8
00:01:32,800 --> 00:01:48,040
 And these students, you know, they learn how to code, and they learn what the tools are and the theory, but they also take philosophy classes and theology classes and integrate our faith into, you know, the design and use of these tools.

9
00:01:48,040 --> 00:01:54,960
 Which I was, you know, working through those problems of what does that look like at the conference last year.

10
00:01:54,960 --> 00:01:59,520
 So for me personally, to see that launched for this fall semester is great.

11
00:01:59,520 --> 00:02:05,560
 And John, how do you see AI transforming classrooms when you talk to teachers or parents or administrators?

12
00:02:05,560 --> 00:02:07,920
 Well, I'll pick up on two points that Dr. Dominguez made.

13
00:02:07,920 --> 00:02:15,000
 The first is that organically, AI has been in our classrooms for many years now, even pre-2022.

14
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:22,720
 I mean, AI was being very subtly used, if not perceptibly by students or teachers.

15
00:02:22,720 --> 00:02:31,800
 So organic use has been around, and certainly since 2022 with ChatGPT, that has very much been a reality that we've had to contend with.

16
00:02:32,040 --> 00:02:42,880
 The second point that I want to spend a little bit of time on is the pedagogy question, because I think that's been the great opportunity that has come up in conversation, especially with K-12 teachers.

17
00:02:42,880 --> 00:02:53,140
 For many of them, the first gut instinct is, oh, this is another cheating tool, which, of course, if used improperly, you know, a tool like ChatGPT can be a cheating tool.

18
00:02:53,140 --> 00:03:00,420
 But it's also a great opportunity to step back and think about what is our philosophy of education?

19
00:03:00,420 --> 00:03:01,420
 Why do we teach?

20
00:03:01,420 --> 00:03:09,120
 Some of the bigger questions that often we don't get to wrestle with because we're so, as teachers, we're so consumed by the task in front of us.

21
00:03:09,120 --> 00:03:23,820
 But the artificial intelligence era has almost forced those conversations to come to the fore, because as soon as you get into policy writing or adjusting your syllabi, you inherently have to ask those questions about what will we allow students to use AI for?

22
00:03:23,900 --> 00:03:25,760
 What will I allow myself to use AI for?

23
00:03:25,760 --> 00:03:35,040
 And then you're actually having a philosophy, like conversation, a pedagogical conversation yourself, which to me has been one of the more exciting opportunities that has come up.

24
00:03:35,040 --> 00:03:35,940
 Yeah, I would agree.

25
00:03:36,480 --> 00:03:41,500
 And John, where do you see those, you know, questions or philosophical moments occurring?

26
00:03:41,500 --> 00:03:47,220
 I think in at least to some degree, it depends on the type of school.

27
00:03:47,220 --> 00:03:48,740
 And this is where it's been very interesting working.

28
00:03:48,740 --> 00:03:52,260
 You know, my particular focus and our focus here is in Catholic education.

29
00:03:52,480 --> 00:03:58,500
 But it's been really interesting seeing how in different educational settings, the priority sets are a little bit different.

30
00:03:58,500 --> 00:04:18,060
 There's one very common or well-known AI school that exists that has really leaned into the utilitarian form of education, which is basically a commodification of skills and knowledge and basic facts, which from our Catholic worldview is completely misaligned.

31
00:04:18,800 --> 00:04:27,720
 You know, the point of education is a formative experience that prepares a student for discipleship in their lives and apostleship, and then ultimately sainthood.

32
00:04:27,720 --> 00:04:31,540
 That's a very different version of education, which asks a different set of questions.

33
00:04:31,540 --> 00:04:40,260
 And again, those are the questions that I think we are able to ask and are forced to ask now with this set of tools that can just do things, automate things for us.

34
00:04:40,880 --> 00:04:41,300
 Yeah.

35
00:04:41,300 --> 00:04:43,300
 I think that's well said, John.

36
00:04:43,300 --> 00:04:43,680
 Yeah.

37
00:04:43,680 --> 00:04:44,620
 I love that.

38
00:04:44,620 --> 00:04:50,200
 And Dr. Dominguez feels like AI is transforming every sector that it touches.

39
00:04:50,200 --> 00:04:57,760
 What, in your perspective, makes Catholic education uniquely equipped to lead in the age of AI?

40
00:04:57,760 --> 00:04:58,220
 Yeah.

41
00:04:58,220 --> 00:05:04,220
 I think it goes, and this is how we actually started our morning session at the workshop.

42
00:05:04,220 --> 00:05:07,280
 It goes back to the question of what is Catholic education for?

43
00:05:07,280 --> 00:05:13,040
 What's the difference between Catholic education and a secular education?

44
00:05:13,040 --> 00:05:18,800
 Is it just that they're learning the same subjects and then the students say prayers or go to mass?

45
00:05:18,800 --> 00:05:21,960
 Or what is the purpose of Catholic education?

46
00:05:22,140 --> 00:05:36,160
 And it's what John said, you know, and in our case, in the Catholic University of America, we have a specific mission written on paper by Pope Leo XIII telling us what we're supposed to do and ordering the bishops to go make it happen.

47
00:05:36,160 --> 00:05:45,520
 And that's to produce worthy ministers and, you know, the best, you know, well-formed citizens for our country and the world.

48
00:05:46,400 --> 00:05:48,520
 That's our job as a university.

49
00:05:48,520 --> 00:05:52,360
 And now AI is this new reality.

50
00:05:52,360 --> 00:06:01,040
 It's a set of tools, but it's also a change of an era in the same way that the printing press or the Industrial Revolution was.

51
00:06:01,040 --> 00:06:02,820
 Things are going to be different on the other side.

52
00:06:02,820 --> 00:06:06,520
 As you said, it's integrating into everything quickly.

53
00:06:07,720 --> 00:06:20,200
 So we have, from our, you know, from our faith, we have 2,000 years of thought, scholarship, and Christ, encounter with Christ on our side to help us think through these things.

54
00:06:20,200 --> 00:06:27,800
 And it's important to, and what we can truly do and make a truth claim about is that we know what a human being is.

55
00:06:27,800 --> 00:06:29,640
 And we know what we're for.

56
00:06:29,640 --> 00:06:31,520
 We know the purpose of our existence.

57
00:06:31,520 --> 00:06:34,660
 We know that God has a plan for us, a unique plan.

58
00:06:35,080 --> 00:06:37,460
 And we can craft an education around that.

59
00:06:37,460 --> 00:06:38,020
 We have.

60
00:06:38,020 --> 00:06:48,260
 And now we've got these set of powerful and potentially dangerous tools that if you don't have that perspective of what a human being is, can lead to terrible things.

61
00:06:48,600 --> 00:06:59,780
 And my friends who are outside of the church or who are, you know, secular humanists and otherwise just very good people and don't want to do bad things, you know, like Google's don't do evil.

62
00:06:59,780 --> 00:07:05,240
 That's an incomplete answer to what you should do, but it's not bad to try to not do evil.

63
00:07:06,060 --> 00:07:18,040
 The problem, the things they struggle with is telling the difference between the simulation of a particular trait of a human being and a real person.

64
00:07:18,040 --> 00:07:25,080
 Like, how do you tell the difference between, you know, these chat GPT outputs and me and you talking?

65
00:07:25,520 --> 00:07:37,100
 And we know the answer between the difference between these things because God made us, you know, Imago Dei in this image and likeness in order to know and love him and to be with him.

66
00:07:37,100 --> 00:07:40,360
 And this is a tool that we're using.

67
00:07:40,360 --> 00:07:45,580
 Now, it's a very dangerous tool, just like a knife can be a very dangerous tool or you can use it.

68
00:07:45,580 --> 00:07:49,120
 I could use a knife to hurt somebody or I could use it to cut my steak.

69
00:07:49,340 --> 00:07:52,200
 So it's the intentionality of the persons.

70
00:07:52,200 --> 00:08:00,760
 You have to understand that, who we are, what are we for, and who are my fellow, you know, travelers on the earth at this time.

71
00:08:00,760 --> 00:08:10,100
 Catholic education gives us the framework and answers for that, that there's just a limit that you can't get with secular education.

72
00:08:10,100 --> 00:08:11,540
 That's, I think, the answer.

73
00:08:11,540 --> 00:08:19,320
 What do you see going on in, you know, higher education as AI continues to transform, as these technologies continue to transform the landscape?

74
00:08:19,320 --> 00:08:26,640
 Yeah, I mean, it's, higher education is in a moment of crisis itself, and I think this is contributing to it.

75
00:08:26,640 --> 00:08:32,860
 It's not the origin of it, but there's a lot of negative factors right now at play in higher ed.

76
00:08:33,540 --> 00:08:48,340
 You know, there's some justly and unjustly, you know, negative views of higher ed, and I think that it does, as a sector, I think, does deserve some correction.

77
00:08:48,340 --> 00:08:50,780
 But it's under, certainly under attack.

78
00:08:53,000 --> 00:08:58,320
 And, you know, pure utilitarianism leads to things like the Holocaust, right?

79
00:08:58,320 --> 00:09:05,020
 That's the ultimate, ultimate result of that type of thinking is just, is horrific, right?

80
00:09:05,020 --> 00:09:09,580
 So we certainly must avoid that direction at all costs.

81
00:09:09,580 --> 00:09:18,940
 And I think people of goodwill who are in these secular universities, many of whom are Catholics themselves, but maybe not in a position to change the mission of the university,

82
00:09:19,660 --> 00:09:22,540
 are looking for people like us to work with.

83
00:09:22,540 --> 00:09:25,140
 And I think we see them there in the room, so they can bring that back.

84
00:09:25,140 --> 00:09:30,680
 So that's, I think, one of our goals here is to be missionaries, send out missionaries into the world.

85
00:09:30,680 --> 00:09:38,040
 It strikes me as providential when I look back at the last roughly 150 years or so, how God has prepared us for this moment.

86
00:09:38,040 --> 00:09:42,100
 We had the Industrial Revolution and the blossoming of Catholic social teaching.

87
00:09:42,100 --> 00:09:46,620
 We had the Theology of the Body unpacked by John Paul II.

88
00:09:48,140 --> 00:09:59,540
 And strangely, we have, at least in the United States, an increasingly secular world that's actually becoming more interested, I think, in some of these deeper existential questions, more open to the teachings of the church in some ways.

89
00:09:59,980 --> 00:10:08,840
 And so in kind of a strange way, I think the, when you put those factors together, the church is, again, providentially able to speak directly to the heart of the matter.

90
00:10:08,840 --> 00:10:13,800
 And then you ask the question, like, how can Catholic schools and Catholic education broadly lead?

91
00:10:13,800 --> 00:10:18,160
 I think it starts by identifying the problem areas and how do we address the problems.

92
00:10:18,160 --> 00:10:21,840
 And for me, when I've worked with teachers, we talk about academic integrity, right?

93
00:10:21,860 --> 00:10:23,380
 That's where most conversations start.

94
00:10:23,380 --> 00:10:24,340
 That's true.

95
00:10:24,340 --> 00:10:27,520
 And it starts there and, for some folks, ends there.

96
00:10:27,520 --> 00:10:34,680
 But I think more deeply, my concerns lie in the disruption that can take place, especially in the writing process.

97
00:10:34,680 --> 00:10:36,120
 Writing is iterative, right?

98
00:10:36,120 --> 00:10:37,740
 It takes successive attempts.

99
00:10:37,740 --> 00:10:44,720
 Drafting improperly used AI can reduce the number of iterations and then severely limit what you produce.

100
00:10:45,420 --> 00:10:54,820
 But I think, actually, that idea of production is also something that's under attack and that we need to think about, that there's a distortion taking place.

101
00:10:54,820 --> 00:10:59,660
 And that's the third that I end up discussing with teachers, is what is the actual ends of an education?

102
00:10:59,660 --> 00:11:04,560
 Again, that's where the Catholic Church and our schools and educational institutions have a particular answer.

103
00:11:04,840 --> 00:11:15,480
 But most deeply is this mirroring idea that some have written and talked about the surprising phenomenon of LLMs sounding more human.

104
00:11:15,480 --> 00:11:22,000
 But I think the deeper concern is actually that we start to sound more like them and that we start to mirror the outputs of LLMs.

105
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:24,140
 And there's a lot of research suggesting that's already happening.

106
00:11:24,140 --> 00:11:26,600
 And I think that's where we start.

107
00:11:26,600 --> 00:11:28,700
 And again, we've got the anthropology.

108
00:11:28,700 --> 00:11:31,560
 We've got the experience, the 2,000 years of wisdom of the church.

109
00:11:31,680 --> 00:11:37,640
 We have to start by identifying what are the problems and opportunities and how do we apply specifically to those problems?

110
00:11:37,640 --> 00:11:39,240
 Yeah.

111
00:11:39,240 --> 00:11:44,500
 Well, I have a question on kind of the LLMs and the algorithms and the automation.

112
00:11:44,500 --> 00:11:48,720
 So I was talking to Father Philip Leray from Boston College, who I adore.

113
00:11:48,720 --> 00:11:51,840
 And we were having a conversation about kind of the opening days of his class.

114
00:11:51,840 --> 00:11:58,400
 And in Boston at that time, there was an advertisement that, I don't know, John, I might have told you this, but it really shocked me.

115
00:11:58,400 --> 00:12:00,740
 It was essentially an advertisement, you know, on a bus stop.

116
00:12:00,740 --> 00:12:01,920
 And there was a number of these throughout.

117
00:12:01,920 --> 00:12:04,140
 And it was a digitalized AI.

118
00:12:04,140 --> 00:12:08,240
 So it was kind of, you know, it was like almost like an animation.

119
00:12:08,240 --> 00:12:12,160
 So you could tell it was not a real person, but it was, of course, in human form and all that.

120
00:12:12,160 --> 00:12:13,460
 And he said, don't hire humans.

121
00:12:13,460 --> 00:12:14,980
 You shouldn't hire humans.

122
00:12:14,980 --> 00:12:16,440
 Hire us robots.

123
00:12:16,440 --> 00:12:20,740
 And one of the kids in the classroom came up to Father Philip.

124
00:12:20,740 --> 00:12:22,360
 And I was like, Father, what's the point?

125
00:12:22,880 --> 00:12:33,760
 Yeah, I think the answer to that is that there is going to be a set of jobs that a machine can do better and is more efficient.

126
00:12:33,760 --> 00:12:36,420
 And I think that's why you're seeing some of these mass layoffs.

127
00:12:36,420 --> 00:12:42,520
 But the reason is because these are very powerful tools that people can use.

128
00:12:42,520 --> 00:12:49,300
 So that's part of what our program at Catholic University is meant to do is to prepare the students.

129
00:12:49,300 --> 00:12:53,120
 You know, even if you're an English major, how do you use these tools?

130
00:12:53,120 --> 00:12:57,040
 But especially the tech people who seems to be more at risk.

131
00:12:57,580 --> 00:13:01,920
 How do you use these set of tools to work in the tech industry?

132
00:13:01,920 --> 00:13:04,240
 And that we can do.

133
00:13:04,240 --> 00:13:06,760
 Like, that's our job as a university.

134
00:13:06,760 --> 00:13:13,360
 So I think the answer is teach your students or, you know, workforce development.

135
00:13:13,360 --> 00:13:20,460
 We've been talking to industries there in the D.C. area who have a great workforce that needs to be reeducated.

136
00:13:20,460 --> 00:13:22,520
 Like, that's what we do.

137
00:13:22,520 --> 00:13:23,720
 We can do that, too.

138
00:13:23,720 --> 00:13:26,240
 So that's the moment.

139
00:13:26,240 --> 00:13:34,980
 If you don't get, if you don't get, learn these new tools or if you don't, if you come out of college unprepared, then you are going to be at a disadvantage.

140
00:13:34,980 --> 00:13:49,220
 And, John, when you, when you look at AI adoption for, you know, classrooms and teaching settings, whether it's in a high school or university, where do you draw the line on where AI should not be used for Catholic, you know, for Catholic education?

141
00:13:49,220 --> 00:13:51,020
 Where is too much AI?

142
00:13:52,700 --> 00:14:00,440
 There's, in Pope Leo's most recent letter that he released about a week ago at this point, he warns of different extremes.

143
00:14:00,440 --> 00:14:08,160
 One of them is the technophobia, which is the let's run back to the caves mentality, which, you know, sometimes sounds attractive.

144
00:14:08,160 --> 00:14:14,000
 But then when you fully think about what that life looks like, probably not as attractive as maybe at an initial glance, it might sound.

145
00:14:14,000 --> 00:14:16,720
 And the other is a digital reductionism, right?

146
00:14:16,720 --> 00:14:21,520
 That at an extreme, again, commodifies learning, eliminates humans from that process.

147
00:14:21,900 --> 00:14:43,340
 And I think, as a starting point, I look at Antiqua at Nova, which directly says that the use of artificial intelligence in, when I say directly, I don't mean this as a quote, but this is a paraphrasing from Antiqua at Nova, that the use of artificial intelligence in educational settings needs to accompany a human relationship between student and teacher.

148
00:14:43,380 --> 00:14:45,080
 And I think that's the right way to frame it.

149
00:14:45,080 --> 00:14:50,860
 Absent that, I think we start to potentially open ourselves up to some real problems.

150
00:14:50,860 --> 00:14:56,900
 I think our classrooms need to be places of physical encounter, as much as that can be possible.

151
00:14:56,900 --> 00:15:03,200
 When we need external technologies, whether that's AI, whether that's a textbook, whatever that is, great.

152
00:15:03,560 --> 00:15:11,580
 But as long as that is oriented towards human flourishing, again, in the physical context of the classroom, facilitating those relationships.

153
00:15:11,580 --> 00:15:14,440
 Now, that's like a high-level place to start.

154
00:15:14,440 --> 00:15:21,160
 But I think that the prudence that's required to actually unpack where do we draw those lines requires a number of different factors.

155
00:15:21,160 --> 00:15:21,900
 How old are your students?

156
00:15:21,900 --> 00:15:23,100
 Developmentally, where are they?

157
00:15:23,100 --> 00:15:27,140
 Again, college setting is very different than the elementary school setting.

158
00:15:27,140 --> 00:15:30,080
 And so I think there's a number of factors that we need to start weighing up.

159
00:15:30,160 --> 00:15:38,760
 But it's those high-level things about the relationship between teacher and student, the incarnational nature of our classrooms that I think really should be the starting points.

160
00:15:38,760 --> 00:15:45,260
 Yeah, I think rather than a line, you know, you asked, where's the line that you don't cross?

161
00:15:45,260 --> 00:15:51,820
 I think it's a bigger question of what's the purpose of this interaction between the person and the machine?

162
00:15:51,820 --> 00:15:53,080
 What's the desired outcome?

163
00:15:54,040 --> 00:16:08,960
 And so we've been thinking about this for the past year as we designed this new use of AI and this new curriculum and kind of settled on three pillars that help guide us to answer the set of questions that are related to what you're saying.

164
00:16:08,960 --> 00:16:25,680
 And the first is that we should conceive of these interactions with a human and an AI or some emergent technology as a human-machine team with the human being as the principal protagonist in this interaction, the center, the human person.

165
00:16:25,680 --> 00:16:31,080
 Since we know, as we talked about earlier, we know what a human being is, made in the image and likeness of God.

166
00:16:31,880 --> 00:16:43,140
 He should be at the center of this interaction with a machine and so there's a proper ordering to this interaction and an improper ordering and the improper ordering leads to bad stuff or can lead to bad stuff.

167
00:16:43,140 --> 00:16:48,580
 So yeah, it should be should be thought of as using this tool for a person.

168
00:16:48,580 --> 00:16:52,240
 And then the second pillar is this flourishing.

169
00:16:52,240 --> 00:16:57,800
 It should open this interaction should open up a window for the human being to flourish.

170
00:16:58,040 --> 00:17:10,300
 There should be a new opportunity for the human to grow in virtue and and that's if you design it on purpose that way, you know, you can you can up your chances that that's likely to happen.

171
00:17:10,300 --> 00:17:23,620
 And you should do you should you should avoid strictly the opposite should never design this type of interaction to encourage vice right to you know which is going to be hurting somebody.

172
00:17:24,120 --> 00:17:32,200
 Like if you designed an artificial girlfriend, like that human that boys that young man is not going to flourish.

173
00:17:32,200 --> 00:17:33,940
 He's not going to grow in virtue.

174
00:17:33,940 --> 00:17:35,680
 He's not going to love.

175
00:17:35,680 --> 00:17:38,120
 So that's number two.

176
00:17:38,120 --> 00:17:45,060
 And then the third is that it that we mentioned it I think earlier this morning, it should lead to an authentic human interaction.

177
00:17:45,060 --> 00:17:58,100
 You know, the example you gave is it should it should lead to, you know, let's we're all in class together for 90 minutes discussing face to face, you know, what we think and asking questions.

178
00:17:58,100 --> 00:17:58,780
 That's it.

179
00:17:58,780 --> 00:18:00,560
 That's an authentic human interaction.

180
00:18:00,560 --> 00:18:00,940
 Right.

181
00:18:00,940 --> 00:18:09,520
 So if it leads to that type of interaction, like maybe you used AI to do some research on on John to prepare for this podcast.

182
00:18:09,740 --> 00:18:10,480
 I absolutely did.

183
00:18:10,480 --> 00:18:20,060
 But here we are, here we are, you know, sharing some jokes and and growing in friendship and that that's a good that's a that's a good human interaction.

184
00:18:20,060 --> 00:18:49,980
 I think to follow up on two of the things you said, one of my favorite use cases that I've I've experienced from or at least heard from from teachers is the idea that they will encourage their students to use whatever the approved version of, you know, Gemini or whatever, whatever the tool is at their school to prepare for in class debates, whether it's from research or even just practicing delivering a, you know, a portion of the debate, having it critiqued by, again, whatever the tool is to better facilitate an in person encounter.

185
00:18:50,060 --> 00:18:51,800
 Because I think that's the right orientation, right?

186
00:18:51,800 --> 00:18:57,080
 I think that the second pillar that you outlined, that idea of human flourishing gets right back to the job question.

187
00:18:57,080 --> 00:19:08,480
 Yeah, because I think I mean, I can speak personally about this, that it's really hard for me at times to separate my own personal identity from my work, because it's so intrinsically just part of who I am, right?

188
00:19:08,480 --> 00:19:11,420
 And that's been my own, you know, journey, but I don't think I'm alone in that.

189
00:19:11,420 --> 00:19:25,860
 And I think especially as we race towards some form of job loss, no matter how big or small that is, there's a potential existential cliff that people are going to face when they realize like, oh, this thing that I did, that defined me in a sense is gone.

190
00:19:25,860 --> 00:19:27,880
 What is the purpose of my life?

191
00:19:28,100 --> 00:19:35,700
 And that's where the question about how do we define and explain human flourishing, this is not a Catholic education issue, this is a Catholic church pastoral issue.

192
00:19:35,700 --> 00:19:40,000
 Well, I mean, that's, that's what partially what Rerum Novarum was about.

193
00:19:40,160 --> 00:19:58,800
 And so I think Rerum Novarum 2.0 that Pope Leo is probably going to write, you know, work is human dignity, like work leads to human dignity, especially for men, just because of the differences in, in families, you know, giving a man a just wage to do honorable work, gives him dignity.

194
00:19:58,800 --> 00:20:05,300
 And if you take that away for some, you know, for some reason, it hurts, like, it really hurts.

195
00:20:05,300 --> 00:20:11,800
 So if yeah, for now, if now your entire profession has been erased, that's like scary.

196
00:20:11,800 --> 00:20:25,240
 And I think it's even more acute right now, because most of the research that I've read is that the job loss currently is impacting junior level employees, which is basically folks coming out of college, because those are the types of tasks that can be automated right now.

197
00:20:26,460 --> 00:20:41,400
 So as we think, again, in parishes and other ministries about how do we, what are the pastoral issues, especially for that demographic of 20 to 25, that's going to be a real need, but then certainly that's going to scale over time as AI improves.

198
00:20:41,400 --> 00:20:54,880
 And also in the optimistic settings where they're like, oh, yeah, don't worry, you know, your material needs, your material goods will be provided at a fraction of the cost, and you'll have more time to do the things that we do want to do, the things of leisure, contemplation, all that stuff, which sounds great.

199
00:20:55,100 --> 00:20:58,220
 But I am very wary of unearned pleasure, unearned comfort.

200
00:20:58,220 --> 00:21:06,020
 Like I, as a man, but also as someone who's industrious and wants to work, I grow so much when I'm learning, when I'm being stretched, when I'm being challenged.

201
00:21:06,020 --> 00:21:16,480
 And I think that, like I am, I think like something that I, I don't know, I don't know if this is directly something in education, but that ability in education for people to find their vocations and then to have a vision of how to get there.

202
00:21:16,560 --> 00:21:16,780
 Yeah.

203
00:21:17,780 --> 00:21:34,540
 Well, I think defining, not even defining, but exploring what true leisure looks like is a great need in like our families and our schools, other institutions, because this is something that people wrote about like 75 years ago, right, or maybe not quite that long ago, but that we yearn for this freedom.

204
00:21:34,900 --> 00:21:38,660
 But when we achieve freedom, what are we going to spend it on?

205
00:21:38,660 --> 00:21:48,020
 And I think, again, there's a great need in our educational institutions to, again, orient us in the right direction to be able to experience leisure if and when that becomes more readily available.

206
00:21:48,020 --> 00:21:50,660
 Yeah, I certainly, I certainly, I certainly need more of that.

207
00:21:50,660 --> 00:21:52,740
 I think, what, what is it called?

208
00:21:52,740 --> 00:21:56,800
 Utropelia, when you're not, you don't, you don't know how to relax.

209
00:21:56,800 --> 00:22:01,980
 Like, I don't know how to like, go on vacation.

210
00:22:01,980 --> 00:22:15,960
 My, my, my wife's grandmother often speaks about how different vacations were for their family after the invention of the car phone, because prior to the car phone, a vacation was true separation.

211
00:22:16,340 --> 00:22:20,320
 But after the car phone, you were always at least sort of accessible.

212
00:22:20,320 --> 00:22:24,120
 And I think with every digital technology since then, that's just been ramped up, right?

213
00:22:24,120 --> 00:22:26,380
 Yeah, now there is no off switch in a weird way.

214
00:22:26,380 --> 00:22:28,800
 Until you go camping in the mountains, which is what we love to do, too.

215
00:22:28,800 --> 00:22:30,080
 Yeah, me too.

216
00:22:30,080 --> 00:22:44,260
 And so just to kind of wind down here, as AI accelerates, Dr. Dominguez and John, what practical steps in training and partnerships and strategic investments can Catholic institutions

217
00:22:45,200 --> 00:22:48,040
 integrate AI effectively to lead in this transformation?

218
00:22:48,040 --> 00:22:54,020
 Well, one, I'll give you just some concrete examples and pull back from there.

219
00:22:54,020 --> 00:23:01,980
 But, so we're, we're a unique university in the United States and that we're the pontifical, the national pontifical university, the only one.

220
00:23:02,520 --> 00:23:05,460
 And founded by the, all the US bishops.

221
00:23:05,460 --> 00:23:11,040
 So in a sense, like we serve, we serve the church of the United States and the bishops.

222
00:23:11,040 --> 00:23:15,740
 And that's our, that's the, one of the main purposes of our university.

223
00:23:16,400 --> 00:23:19,800
 And this is a leadership class that's extremely important in the church.

224
00:23:19,800 --> 00:23:26,080
 And, um, probably very few of them are current in AI, maybe one or two.

225
00:23:26,080 --> 00:23:32,740
 Like the guys who have their podcasts are probably, probably up to speed on a lot of stuff, but many of them aren't.

226
00:23:33,180 --> 00:23:40,860
 So, um, this is, this is the code I use for it as a more polite term, but we've created a bootcamp, AI bootcamp for bishops.

227
00:23:40,860 --> 00:23:42,000
 Yeah.

228
00:23:42,000 --> 00:23:48,620
 Which is going to go live here, um, hopefully pretty soon before their November meeting, but that, and it's just kind of basic stuff.

229
00:23:48,620 --> 00:23:59,000
 It's a set of 15 minute modules that Taylor black has helped us put together and, um, it's asynchronous and delivered online and it's far walled off.

230
00:23:59,000 --> 00:24:01,120
 So it's not currently not publicly accessible.

231
00:24:01,120 --> 00:24:03,080
 It's just, just for those men right now.

232
00:24:03,080 --> 00:24:10,360
 Um, but that's, that's because they need to understand like the language, like the words, that's where we began.

233
00:24:10,360 --> 00:24:12,300
 And then, you know, what are the set of tools?

234
00:24:12,300 --> 00:24:14,400
 What are the kind of good things that you can do with this?

235
00:24:14,400 --> 00:24:17,260
 How can you use this for your diocese, for your business?

236
00:24:17,860 --> 00:24:19,920
 You know, how can you, how can you help your priests?

237
00:24:19,920 --> 00:24:23,080
 So a series of modules like that.

238
00:24:23,080 --> 00:24:32,320
 So that's something, um, that we're well-suited to, to do given our, uh, you know, our existence as the Catholic university of America.

239
00:24:32,320 --> 00:24:34,680
 Um, so there's that.

240
00:24:34,680 --> 00:24:39,600
 And then there's, then there's those, just the education of our students that I mentioned before.

241
00:24:39,600 --> 00:24:44,160
 Um, and then producing shows like this, right.

242
00:24:44,160 --> 00:24:46,180
 We have to think through this stuff.

243
00:24:47,100 --> 00:24:53,000
 It's been really heartening to see different individuals and institutions, uh, jumping into the fray.

244
00:24:53,000 --> 00:24:56,440
 Um, there have been frameworks released there.

245
00:24:56,440 --> 00:25:05,560
 I mean, even this morning in our, uh, education breakout, we had, uh, a gentleman talking about a set of resources that he's putting online and making available for parishes to think through.

246
00:25:06,080 --> 00:25:11,640
 You know, again, these core questions of what are the terms, what is AI, how do we approach it?

247
00:25:11,640 --> 00:25:15,960
 Um, so the growing bank of resources, I, it has been good.

248
00:25:16,040 --> 00:25:23,020
 I think the only challenge we might run into there is that we might overwhelm, uh, the faithful who, who are looking for, okay, where do I go to get a good information?

249
00:25:23,020 --> 00:25:24,860
 There's 300 frameworks.

250
00:25:24,860 --> 00:25:27,380
 There's 300, uh, sets of video modules.

251
00:25:27,380 --> 00:25:35,140
 So I, I think that, um, the more that we can be precise about, okay, this is a particular need that my institution or me individually that I can fill the better.

252
00:25:35,380 --> 00:25:45,760
 Um, but I, I think that I love the idea of addressing the language that we use because there's so many interesting semantic questions around artificial intelligence, even just that term itself is fascinating.

253
00:25:45,760 --> 00:25:51,000
 So to, to start by unpacking what is that term and then some of the related definitions and ideas.

254
00:25:51,000 --> 00:25:58,220
 And then I think the fundamental orientations about, um, instead of just saying, let's use AI, it's what are the problems you're trying to solve?

255
00:25:58,220 --> 00:25:59,060
 Okay, great.

256
00:25:59,060 --> 00:26:02,660
 Let's start with those and then start attacking them by plugging in solutions.

257
00:26:02,940 --> 00:26:07,140
 So those are the kinds of, uh, resources that I think are most helpful for folks.

258
00:26:07,140 --> 00:26:07,460
 Yeah.

259
00:26:07,460 --> 00:26:09,520
 That is fantastic.

260
00:26:09,520 --> 00:26:14,560
 Um, thank you so much, Dr. Aaron Dominguez and John Brayer for joining me today on this podcast.

261
